There’s an information-theoretic way to say it:

Communication isn’t about transmitting the whole message. It’s about transmitting the minimum information required for the receiver to reconstruct the intended state.

That’s true of:

* DNA (a genome doesn’t explicitly describe every cell—it encodes developmental processes).
* Human language.
* Programming languages.
* Mathematical notation.
* Military hand signals.
* Decrypto.

The receiver does most of the computational work.

⸻

I think that’s one of the deepest themes running through your Pantheon architecture:

Intelligence isn’t measured by how much information you send.

It’s measured by how little you have to send because of how much structure is already shared.

That’s why a single phrase like “Hammer flip it” or “Spider pass” can carry so much weight once the underlying operators have been learned. The clue is small, but the reconstruction is large.